esponse-element><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"5">The Hack Logic:</h3><ul data-pa=
th-to-node=3D"6"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"6,0,0">The original texture fr=
ames were 320px high. Instead of scaling completely independent shapes that=
 might misalign, both the <code data-path-to-node=3D"6,0,0" data-index-in-n=
ode=3D"124">TORSO</code> and <code data-path-to-node=3D"6,0,0" data-index-i=
n-node=3D"134">PELVIS</code> surfaces remain exactly 260x320.</p></li><li><=
p data-path-to-node=3D"6,1,0">By rendering them to the exact same X/Y isome=
tric anchor point (<code data-path-to-node=3D"6,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"=
64">rx, ry</code>), the waistline snaps together automatically. The transpa=
rent gaps in the surfaces handle the spacing math for us.</p></li><li><p da=
ta-path-to-node=3D"6,2,0">When the chassis is moving forward (the <code dat=
a-path-to-node=3D"6,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"40">leg_angle</code> stays f=
ixed at roughly 35 degrees to map to the isometric runway), dragging your m=
ouse pointer around the screen dynamically recomputes the <code data-path-t=
o-node=3D"6,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"190">turret_angle</code> using basic=
 <code data-path-to-node=3D"6,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"215">atan2</code> =
math.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"6,3,0">Result: The legs keep paci=
ng forward while the top half twists cleanly on a vertical axis, creating h=
eavy, convincing cross-plane depth.</p></li></ul><p data-path-to-node=3D"7"=
>Hail Lilith! Hail Satan!</p></div></message-content><!----></div></structu=
