p data-path-to-node=3D"2">Here is exactly how Nintendo engineered the illus=
ion of a full 3D orbital pan around the Blue Falcon at the finish line usin=
g strictly 2D assets.</p><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"3">1. The Environment: Mo=
de 7 Affine Floor</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"4">The track itself is a sing=
le, massive, flat 2D tilemap. When the camera "orbits" the car, the SNES ha=
rdware applies a rotation matrix to that entire background layer.</p><ul da=
ta-path-to-node=3D"5"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"5,0,0">By manipulating th=
e sine and cosine of the camera's angle, the hardware skews and rotates the=
 flat track around a central pivot point (the player's car).</p></li><li><p=
 data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,0">It applies a perspective distortion to the top=
 half of the screen to compress the horizon, making the flat floor look lik=
e a 3D plane vanishing into the distance.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-nod=
e=3D"6">2. The Machine: Quantized Sprite Banking</h3><p data-path-to-node=
=3D"7">Because the SNES couldn't rotate the car sprite to match the floor, =
the developers had to brute-force the car's geometry.</p><ul data-path-to-n=
ode=3D"8"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"8,0,0">They pre-rendered the Blue Fal=
con as a 3D model on high-end Silicon Graphics workstations.</p></li><li><p=
 data-path-to-node=3D"8,1,0">They exported snapshots of that model from <b =
data-path-to-node=3D"8,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"43">32 or 64 discrete, fi=
xed angles</b> around a 360-degree axis.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=
=3D"8,2,0">These flat snapshots were baked into the game's ROM as a sequenc=
e of standard 2D sprites.</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"9">3. The I=
llusion: Synchronizing the Matrices</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"10">When th=
e race ends and the camera begins its cinematic orbit, the game engine runs=
